[C]
Date: Thu 11 Aug 2022
Source: Times of Israel [abridged, edited]
https://www.timesofisrael.com/uk-working-with-israel-ny-on-polio-probe-as-more-virus-found-in-london-sewage/


British health authorities have announced they are working with their counterparts in Israel and the United States to trace the source of polioviruses found in sewage samples from areas in North and North East London, and are launching a vaccination campaign to boost children's immunity.

In June [2022], authorities announced that they had detected traces of a form of polio derived from a vaccine strain at a sewage treatment plant in north-east London.

Since then, the virus, eradicated in the United Kingdom in 2003, has been detected in 8 boroughs of the capital, with "genetic diversity" suggesting "virus transmission", according to the health services.

"No one has been diagnosed with the virus and the risk to the population is low," Health Minister Steve Barclay said in a statement.

According to the World Health Organization (WHO), only 1 in 200 polio infections leads to paralysis; most people have no symptoms.

The British health agency said it was "working closely" with the authorities in New York, but also in Israel, to study possible links between "recent incidents" reported.

Israel's Health Ministry did not immediately respond to a request for comment on the investigation.

Last month [July 2022], authorities in New York announced that they had detected polio in an Orthodox Jew in Rockland County, marking the 1st case of polio in the United States in nearly a decade.

The Global Polio Eradication Initiative said on [28 Jul 2022] that this case was genetically linked to virus samples found in London and at the Sorek sewage treatment plant in Israel.

Officials in Rockland and Orange counties, areas north of New York with large and growing haredi populations, later said traces of the virus had been found in sewage samples.

Israel diagnosed its 1st case in decades in March [2022], in a 4-year-old child from Jerusalem. Several other asymptomatic cases were found in other children, and health officials launched a nationwide vaccination campaign that they say has raised the immunization rate to 96% among infants.

No link has been confirmed between the virus samples and the Jewish community. However, authorities in New York and the United Kingdom have noted that the virus has been found in areas with lower vaccination rates. "We know that the areas of London where poliovirus is transmitted have some of the lowest vaccination rates," said Dr Vanessa Saliba, consultant epidemiologist at the UK Health Security Agency. "This is where the virus spreads in these communities and it puts residents who are not fully vaccinated at greater risk.

